He who, by a quicker motion of the throat, can now suspend the song for a while, now protract, and now interrupt it with groanS, or laughter, or can imitate the bellowing of abull, or the tremulous voice of a kid,—-he will gain universal applause. No European would deny that tliese'savage singers inspired him with a kind of melancholy and horror, so much are the ears, and even the mind affected by that deadly chaunting, the darkness adding greatly to the mournful effect. One of the singers rattles a gourd filled with maize seedS‚-to the time of the music. Some- times the gourd alone preludes the singing, as in a band of musicians ; at otherS, it follows the voice of the singer, and very seldom rests sor ever so little a while. When two are singing at a time, it is wonderful to hear so much concord in such discordant voices. You never observe them hesitate or pause: for they do not sing extemporaneously, but what has been long studied beforehand.
